		<div class="postbody">
			<div class="postrow has_after_content">
				
				
				<h2 class="title icon icon0">
					How to save money when buying videogames
				</h2>
				

						
							
							
							
						
						
				<div class="content ">
					<div id="post_message_1469232">
						<blockquote class="postcontent restore ">
							It only occurred to me after I promised to do this that it might come off as kind of dickish, but regardless of the consequences it is important to finish what you started, so here we go! <br />
<br />
Disclaimer: These are from my own experiences, you might already have methods that work better for you.<br />
<br />
<font size="4">Part I: The Basics</font><br />
<br />
<a href="http://www.cheapassgamer.com" target="_blank" rel="nofollow">www.cheapassgamer.com</a><br />
<br />
For some people this might be all you need to know; the slickdeals of the video game world, CAG is a community of people who find and share great deals. Be sure to use the forums as well as the front page, and you will find everything from the weekly deals at Best Buy and Gamestop, to the Dell PS3 discounts (one currently going on until the 26th btw), to deals off of Steam.<br />
<br />
<font size="4">Part II: When and when not to use Gamestop</font><br />
<br />
I don't use Gamestop as much as I used to, but they are still my second most used place for videogame purchases. Reasons to use Gamestop?<br />
a) If you prefer physical stores, or don't want to wait on mail<br />
b) If you want to take advantage of their various promotions (I got Star Ocean with free day-of-release shipping, and Valkyria with a free mini-artbook)<br />
c) They are more dependable with new releases, assuming you pre-ordered, Amazon sometimes ships new releases late<br />
d) If you primarily want to deal in trade-ins and used games<br />
<br />
The main drawback to Gamestop is that they are crooks and will squeeze you for as much as you are worth. <img src="images/smilies/tongue.gif" border="0" alt="" title="Stick Out Tongue" class="inlineimg" /> They milk old prices for as long as possible before shifting to global price drops. I few months ago I was looking for deals on Battlefield: Bad company, and their used copies cost the same as a new copy off of Amazon. In general, you don't shop at Gamestop to save money, you shop at Gamestop because it feels dependable.<br />
<br />
Now they do have extensive trade in and used games programs, you can even sign up for a special service  to get additional discounts (Edge? Or something). Generally you are going to get the bum end of the deal here, but some people pay for all their games this way. Whether it is more economical than just renting the dang things in the first place I don't know, since I don't make use of this service.<br />
<br />
<font size="4">Part III: How to make the most of Amazon</font><br />
<br />
Amazon has been my preferred source of all my videogames for years now. Every now and then CAG points me in a better deal elsewhere, but Amazon has the most consistently good prices.<br />
<br />
For starters, they usually have a default 3 dollar discount, even on preorders. No tax depending on area, cheaper shipping, including free shipping if you are patient (which you will need to be for my next tip). They are quicker to accept global price drops, will sometimes match another company's deals, and occassionally have temporary price drops themselves. Oh right, and they have a special section labeled the &quot;game deal of the day&quot;. It is usually crap, but you can sometimes get 20 dollars off a new release this way.<br />
<br />
Anyway, this is what I do. Set up a wishlist account on Amazon of all the games you are interesting in playing but don't want to pay full price for. You can buy games straight from your wishlist, so it will update according to any price drops active at the time. I can tell you for example that Fear 2 is getting discounted by 15 dollars across all platforms at the moment.<br />
<br />
Check every few days, and this makes a pretty simple way to save money. Just don't get carried away. Temporary price drops are common, don't feel obligated to take advantage of every sale. Also keep in mind that some products are more resistant to price drops than others. Fear 2 is getting discounted because it isn't selling out. I waited a year for Twilight Princess to budge even an inch and it never did. Heavenly Sword also never dropped in price, I had to get it through a Deal of the Day.<br />
<br />
Please note that CAG will not post every Amazon price drop.<br />
<br />
Edit: Removed the information on the ECA, as the coupon deal they had offerred is no longer available thanks to people who exploited said deal!<br />
<br />
<font size="4">Part IV: Ebay is a sometimes food</font><br />
<br />
Sometimes a game is just too rare to find at a reasonable price new. Sometimes used deals at Gamestop and Amazon are outrageous. Sometimes you have to resort to Ebay. This isn't all bad, you will sometimes find really good deals on Ebay, even on new products. It is very time consuming though, because you don't want to get scammed.<br />
<br />
Amazon Marketplace serves a similar function as Ebay. Always be sure to read the buyer feedback, and stick with sellers with high ratings. It is also important to note the location of the seller. Someone from Hong Kong for example, is likely selling a bootleg. Sellers with their own Ebay stores and professional write ups are preferred.<br />
<br />
Also be aware of the shipping charges. Some sellers will sell an item at a very low price, and then jack up the shipping like mad.<br />
 <br />
<br />
<font size="5">Appendixes</font><br />
<br />
Things I have not tried myself<br />
<br />
<font size="4">Part V: Tips for Europeans</font><br />
<br />
In the war against the EU 20 years from now, top scientists sent robots back in time to sabotage Amazon and Steam in order ensure europeans cannot get great game deals, thus weakening their virtual armies in the future.<br />
<br />
In response, the EU sent back Kyle Reese, who started a business in Canada with lax import restrictions. Ensuring their virtual armies remain uncontested, but inadvertently creating a new superpower, the Land of the Frozen Sun.<br />
<br />
<a href="http://www.videogamesplus.ca" target="_blank" rel="nofollow">www.videogamesplus.ca</a> (not .com)<br />
<br />
Please note the region encoding of whatever you buy, some systems are region free and some are not. <br />
<br />
<b>Corollary 1: Yaxa's chart of region coding goodness</b><br />
<br />
<ul><li style=""><b>DS</b>: DS games are <font color="green">region free</font>.</li><li style=""><b>DSi</b>: DSi games are <font color="red">region coded</font>, but regular DS games will play on any DSi.</li><li style=""><b>PS3</b>: PS3 games are <font color="green">region free</font>. PS1 and PS2 games are <font color="red">region coded</font> and that restriction is enforced on the PS3. Blu-ray movies are <font color="orange">optionally region coded</font>.</li><li style=""><b>PSP</b>: PSP games are <font color="green">region free</font>. UMD movies are <font color="red">region coded</font>.</li><li style=""><b>Wii</b>: Wii games are <font color="red">region coded</font>. GameCube games are <font color="red">region coded</font>.</li><li style=""><b>Xbox 360</b>: Games are <font color="orange">optionally region coded</font>. <a href="http://www.play-asia.com/paOS-00-3-xbox360_compatibility_guide-49-en.html" target="_blank" rel="nofollow">Xbox 360 Region Compatibility List</a>.</li></ul><br />
<br />
<b>Contributors: Droigan, Yaxa</b><br />
<br />
<font size="4">Part VI: An Alternative to Gamestop Trading</font><br />
<br />
<a href="http://www.swaptree.com/" target="_blank" rel="nofollow">http://www.swaptree.com/</a><br />
<br />
A place where you can trade books, music, DVDs or video games.<br />
<br />
It looks like a website that facilitates trades between users, as opposed to trading with a business for store credit.<br />
<br />
You can also try Half.com, a branch of Ebay.<br />
<br />
<b>Contributors: Lunal, Gariel Halliwell</b><br />
<br />
<font size="4">Part VII: Miscellaneous</font><br />
<br />
1) I've never used it, but <a href="http://www.play-asia.com/" target="_blank" rel="nofollow">http://www.play-asia.com/</a> is supposed to be a good site for importing Japanese games.<br />
<br />
2) Steam has frequent deals, usually on the weekends. CAG will post these.<br />
<br />
3) If you are willing to do some digging you can find discout games both in the bargain bins in stores like Target, and in places you might not expect, such as &quot;Big Lots and Half-Price Books&quot;.<br />
<br />
<b>Contributors: Cantatus, Yyidth</b>
						</blockquote>
					</div>

					
				</div>
			</div>
			
